There was no reason to stop receiving clean Lake Huron water. It was delivered thru a contract with DSWD, who begged Flint not to cancel.
There was never a way to treat the toxic water. The Flint Water Treatment Plant needs $100M in repairs. Why intentionally serve poison?
For over 50 years, Flint received clean water from Lake Huron. Why were they secretly switched to toxic Flint River water?

a lot of scale opportunities are not used today. eg batch send from services is asymptotically 5x scale. some passed on costs rather than do
use renewed sense of collaboration among ecosystem companies to work together on scaling as a grand challenge via adoption & best practices.
work spent preparing for, testing and re-architecting systems to handle two coins would be time better spent integrating segwit for scale.
sooner see spoonnet used in 2018/2019 than a controversial, rushed & featureless HF that results in a coin split and confidence loss.
we should use hard-forks only for uncontroversial things to avoid splits. and with ample time from feature design and fork design & testing.
constitutional referendum is an expensive process, that devolves into wrong thinking about votes. # Bitcoin is not a democracy, it's better.
you no more want a contentious HF to deploy a 2MB scale/security trade-off, than a UK brexit on Brits right to call orange jam marmalade.
just how change management is done on complex systems: multiple design ideas, design review, put ego aside & time for extensive open review.
can't have invasive (or even minor) changes where peer review is saying "that makes no sense". mistakes are how planes fall out of the sky.
that @ garzik keeps making left field claims & confused rationales with tech community saying huh? shows the importance of wide peer review.
simple criteria for soft-fork adoption are that it be opt-in, benefit to a range of users, not hurting other users, and of manageable risk.
modern soft-forks are opt-in: segwit is opt-in per block, per-transaction and individual adoption. fund risk to invasive change is minimised
if the delivered features have consensus, which segwit did already starting in 2015 as a scale compromise, a soft-fork is safer and faster.
a hard-fork is nominally more "choice", but an unwanted, forced choice that splits currency and erodes confidence is also bad.
i went through it all before with @ jgarzik on IRC for a few hours: a change can be evil or good. the deployment method is separate.
so why don't you become part of the solution and offer to help companies adopt. you run a consulting company: dont they usually say "can do"
@ jgarzik is a funny guy. he thinks hard-forks can be rushed but soft-forks take years. the wallet I use is already ready. most are.
